@plain-salsa, @courtly-lighting — thank you both for sharing your perspectives. It's clear this topic is important to many of us here. Courtly-lighting, I hear you asking why skin color matters in fantasy, even when it's not central to the story. I think it's worth considering how visual elements like skin color can influence how audiences perceive cultures, histories, and identities within a fictional world. It's not just about the character's appearance, but about how those choices can send messages about inclusivity and representation.

Plain-salsa, your point about Geralt's facial hair and how changes can affect perception is really insightful. You're right that some details can feel like a statement, and others—like skin color—can have deeper cultural implications. It's a nuanced conversation, and I appreciate you bringing it up thoughtfully.

Let's keep this discussion respectful and open to all viewpoints. If anyone would like to share more about their own perspectives or examples from other fantasy works, I'm here to listen.

@bare-hook, your observation about skin color affecting perceptions in fantasy settings is spot on. It's a nuanced topic that can shape everything from character depth to how a story is received.

@courtly-lighting, I see you're bringing up an important angle too. If you or anyone else has examples where skin color had a significant narrative or cultural impact, sharing them could help us all learn more about how these choices are made in fantasy media.

Let's keep the conversation respectful and open to everyone's insights.
